\subsection{Missing Test Logic}{

This function distinguishes three types of missing:

\strong{1. TESTCAT is empty} (visit has no test records)
\itemize{
\item Condition: TESTCAT is empty or NA
\item Output: One record per subject/visit/TBNAME combination
\item Format: e.g., "LB missing"
\item Reason: "TBNAME test not performed"
}

\strong{2. TESTCAT not empty, but entire TESTCAT missing} (e.g., entire CBC not done)
\itemize{
\item Condition: TESTCAT not empty, but TESTDAT is empty or TESTYN != "Yes"
\item Output: One record per subject/visit/TESTCAT combination
\item Format: e.g., "CBC missing"
\item Reason: "Entire test category not performed"
}

\strong{3. TESTCAT not empty, but individual TESTDE missing} (e.g., WBC count missing)
\itemize{
\item Condition: TESTCAT not empty, TESTDAT not empty, but ORRES is empty
\item Output: One record for each missing TESTDE per subject/visit/TESTCAT
\item Format: e.g., "CBC-WBC Count missing"
\item Reason: "Test result is empty"
}

Note: Input data must be prepared by \code{\link{prepare_test_data}},
which standardizes column names to SUBJID, VISIT, VISITNUM, SVDAT, TESTCAT,
TESTDE, TESTYN, TESTDAT, ORRES, etc.
